  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Given a complex surface <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="script">X</mi></math> with singularities of class T and no nontrivial holomorphic vector field, endowed with a Kähler class <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math> , we consider smoothings <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> , where <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub></math> is a Kähler class on <math altimg="si100.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub></math> degenerating to <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math> . Under an hypothesis of nondegeneracy of the smoothing at each singular point, we prove that if <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="script">X</mi></math> admits a constant scalar curvature Kähler metric in <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math> , then <math altimg="si100.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub></math> admits a constant scalar curvature Kähler metric in <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub></math> for small t .</subfield>
